From: jdough@sinkhole.unf.edu (Joseph Dougherty)
Subject: Re: CD Rom Recommendations?
Date: Sat, 25 Sep 1993 20:06:03 GMT

Cory West (corywest@kennel.rice.edu) wrote:

:       Well, I have been using my Sony CDU-31A for a while now
: and want to get a disc with Linux stuff on it so that I can reclaim
: some of my precious hard disk space.  I'd love to get recommendations
: from anyone who has purchased one of the many linux discs.
: Thanks.

        I just received and installed the Trans-Ameritech CDROM. The
installation went very well, and there are multiple options
for installations. SLS 1.02 is there, along with a "live" 1.02 that
you can run directly from the CDROM. 1.03 is also there, which has 
kernel support for your SONY CD (although I've heard about bugginess
in that patch level. There's also a Slackware installation on the disk,
alone with a 386BSD complete distribution, a directory filled with DOS
and Windows stuff (from Simtel) and two directories of sound and picture
files.
        For $30, you really can't beat this. They appear to have tested
the Linux installations very well. 
        I recommend this for someone getting into Linux or
returning to it after some time (like me!).

--


Joe Dougherty
University of North Florida     
jdough@unf6.cis.unf.edu (preferred) cop0812@unf1vm.cis.unf.edu
