From: yci@netcom.com (Yggdrasil Computing)
Subject: Re: El cheapo CD with Linux
Date: Sat, 25 Sep 1993 23:25:27 GMT

In article <1993Sep25.211355.14431@novell.com> tporczyk@novell.com (Tony Porczyk) writes:
>I just saw a rather slow CD that nevertheless supported Kodak
>multi-session format.  It was called Panasonic CR 562.  I wonder if
>anyone used it successfully with Linux?

        The Panasonic CR-562B is a nice double speed CDROM drive
with a soundblaster style interface.

        The Panasonic CR-562B is one of eight drives here on which
the upcoming Yggdrasil LGX production release was tested.  The CR-562B
subjectively seemed to be the fastest, faster even than the Texel dm3024,
although the fast Toshiba SCSI CDROM was not tested.  The CR-562B was
tested connected to the TopTek "universal CDROM interface" that it
comes with, connected to a SoundBlaster Pro, and connected to a
SoundBlaster 16ASP.  The CR-562B never exhibited any problems, and
neither did the other soundblaster compatible driver, the LaserMate.

        There was, however, one anonomoly with the TopTek CDROM
controller.  There is a 486DX2/66 Opti chipset EISA/VLB motherboard
here that freezes if you start X windows with the TopTek CDROM controller
present.  The problem is reproducible with different video cards,
and seems to be a function of the presence of the TopTek card rather
than the drive.  The problem does not occur the other motherboard on
which this was run.

        Eberhard Moenkeberg's Linux soundblaster CDROM driver is new,
so it isn't built into of any standard Linux distribution yet, although
it is possible that the source has made it onto one of the FTP snapshots
on CD that are floating around.  This driver is, however, built into the
LGX production release, which is coming out next week.  You can get the
source code for the driver by anonymous FTP from ftp.gwdg.de in
pub/linux/cdrom.  If you want the source code for the version of the
driver that is on the LGX production release, that is in
netcom.com:pub/yggdrasil/misc/sbpcd.c.  The LGX version of the
driver automatically scans the different possible IO addresses, uses
the kernel's IO port reservation package to avoid stepping on other
IO devices or being stepped on, and adds support for the additional
port addresses that the SoundBlaster 16ASP can use.

